Date:  0/0/1976
Source:  History of Hawke's Bay
Author:  WILSON
Vol / Page:  212
Edition:
Quote:  There were two classes of offenders - those who leased land from the natives and paid them rent, and those who allowed their sheep and cattle to graze on native land and refused to pay rent for such grazing. Much ill-feeling arose between the latter class and the natives, who frequently drove off the cattle or sheep to a distance and held them till their demands for 'grass money' were paid.
